        <div class="cover-sub">Content Briefs · Scoring · AI Draft · SERP Insights · Reports</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- BODY -->
  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">
        <p class="lede-p"><strong>Rankability is the cheapest content optimiser in the serious-tools tier.</strong> It is also a tool that will not move your traffic unless you have writers and a publishing cadence already lined up behind it. After 30 days inside Starter and Pro — plus interviews with 10 paying customers spanning solo bloggers, in-house teams, and agencies — here is the honest 2026 verdict, where Rankability beats Surfer and Clearscope, and where you should stop optimising single articles and start solving the real bottleneck.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">ℹ️ Editorial disclosure</div>
          <p>This review was written and published by theStacc, a competing product in the broader SEO content space. We have a commercial interest as a done-for-you alternative. Every feature claim and price was verified against Rankability's public pricing page as of Q2 2026.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-tldr">
          <div class="callout-label">⚡ TL;DR — The 30-second verdict</div>
          <p><strong>Buy Rankability if</strong> you already have a writer (in-house or freelance) and want a content optimisation editor that beats Surfer on price and matches Clearscope on scoring quality. Starter at $49/mo is the best value in the category. <strong>Skip it if</strong> you do not have writers — the editor alone will not produce articles. If you want traffic without assembling an SEO stack, theStacc handles writing, optimisation, and publishing end-to-end from $99/mo.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="inline-cta">
          <div class="cta-copy">
            <h4>Want traffic, not another scoring tool?</h4>
            <p>Get a <strong>free SEO audit</strong> in 24 hours. We'll show you the keywords you're missing, the technical fixes that move the needle, and your competitors' content gaps — no sales call, no obligation.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="cta-action">
            <a href="/demo/" class="cta-btn-inline">Get my free audit <span>→</span></a>
            <span class="cta-meta">24-hour delivery · No card</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-stacc">theStacc vs Rankability — where we are honestly better (and worse)</h2>
        <p>We compete for the same content-budget dollar but solve very different problems. Read the comparison first.</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Rankability</th><th>theStacc</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td>Starting price</td><td>$49/mo</td><td>$99/mo</td></tr>
              <tr><td>NLP content scoring</td><td class="cell-yes">Excellent</td><td>Built into our workflow</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Content brief generator</td><td class="cell-yes">Yes — strong</td><td class="cell-yes">Yes — built-in</td></tr>
              <tr><td>AI writing assist</td><td class="cell-yes">Drafts paragraphs</td><td class="cell-yes">Full original articles</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Keyword research</td><td class="cell-no">Semantic only — bring your own</td><td class="cell-yes">Topic + cluster planning</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Articles produced for you</td><td class="cell-no">No — editor only</td><td class="cell-yes">Monthly publishing cadence</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Auto-publishes to your CMS</td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td class="cell-yes">WordPress · Webflow · Ghost</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Google Business Profile posts</td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td class="cell-yes">GBP posts included</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Done-for-you (no workflow to run)</td><td class="cell-no">DIY — you optimise + publish</td><td class="cell-yes">Fully managed</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Real monthly cost for SEO content</strong></td><td>$2,000–$5,500 (tool + writers)</td><td><strong>$99 flat</strong></td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Where Rankability wins:</strong> if you have a writer and want the cheapest serious optimiser, the Starter plan is unbeaten on value. <strong>Where theStacc wins:</strong> if your bottleneck is "producing and publishing" rather than "optimising drafts". Pick by the job, not the brand.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is Rankability?</h2>
        <p>Rankability is a content optimisation platform built around <strong>NLP scoring against ranking competitors</strong>. You give it a target keyword. It pulls the top 10–30 ranking results, extracts the key terms and topics those pages use, and gives you a score for your draft based on how well it matches that semantic profile. The premise is simple: if you cover what the ranking pages cover (and a little more), you have a much higher chance of ranking yourself.</p>

        <p>The product does five things:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Content brief generator</strong> — outlines, H2s/H3s, semantic terms, suggested word count</li>
          <li><strong>NLP scoring editor</strong> — real-time score as you write or paste a draft</li>
          <li><strong>SERP insights</strong> — top-ranking pages, their key terms, link profile snippets</li>
          <li><strong>AI writing assistance</strong> — drafts paragraphs from the brief on demand</li>
          <li><strong>Reports + team workflow</strong> — shareable briefs, white-label on higher tiers</li>
        </ol>

        <p>What Rankability is <em>not</em>: a full keyword research tool, an SEO suite (no rank tracking, no backlink analysis, no site audit), or a publishing layer. It assumes you already know your keyword and have a writer. It makes the writer's draft rank-worthy.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">ℹ️ Company background</div>
          <p>Rankability launched in 2022 and is built by an SEO-practitioner team rather than a generalist SaaS company. The product positioning is explicit: cheaper than Surfer, simpler than Clearscope, focused on the scoring methodology that actually correlates with ranking improvements. Smaller user base than the incumbents, but a strong reputation among agencies that have switched off Surfer for cost reasons.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="features">Rankability features — the full 2026 walkthrough</h2>
        <p>The feature surface is intentionally tight. Here is what matters in daily use.</p>

        <h3>1. Content brief generator</h3>
        <p>Drop in a target keyword. Rankability returns a brief with:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Recommended H2s and H3s</strong> derived from the top-ranking pages</li>
          <li><strong>Target word count</strong> based on the average of the top-10</li>
          <li><strong>Semantic terms to include</strong> grouped by importance</li>
          <li><strong>FAQ suggestions</strong> from People Also Ask and competitor sections</li>
          <li><strong>Internal-link suggestions</strong> based on the surrounding content cluster</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The briefs are notably cleaner than Surfer's, which over-includes terms and forces writers to cut. Rankability's curation is tighter — fewer false-positive terms make the writer's life easier.</p>

        <h3>2. NLP scoring editor</h3>
        <p>Paste a draft or write in the editor. Rankability scores your content out of 100 against the ranking pages' semantic profile in real time. Each missing or under-covered term shows up in the sidebar with frequency targets. Hit the target frequencies and your score climbs.</p>

        <p>The scoring methodology weights semantic relevance over raw keyword matching — closer to Clearscope's approach than Surfer's keyword-density-heavy model. In our testing, hitting an 80+ Rankability score correlated with ranking gains more reliably than hitting equivalent Surfer scores.</p>

        <h3>3. SERP insights</h3>
        <p>For any target keyword, Rankability surfaces the top-ranking pages, their domain authority, word count, key terms, and notable structural patterns (lists, tables, images, video). Useful for writers building briefs from scratch without bouncing into Ahrefs.</p>

        <h3>4. AI writing assistance</h3>
        <p>The AI Draft feature generates paragraphs from the brief. It is grounded in the brief's terms and structure, so output is more usable than a blank ChatGPT prompt. Still needs human editing, fact-checking, and original insight to actually rank.</p>

        <h3>5. Team workflow + white-label</h3>
        <p>Agency plan gives you white-label briefs (client-branded PDFs), team seats, and shared workspaces. Smaller in-app collaboration story than Clearscope but cheaper by a wide margin.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">⚠️ What it does not do</div>
          <p>No full keyword research with volume and difficulty (you still need Ahrefs, Semrush, or Mangools). No site audit. No rank tracking. No backlink data. No CMS publishing. Rankability is a scoring editor — best paired with one research tool, one writer, and one publishing workflow.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="pricing">Rankability pricing — what it really costs in 2026</h2>
        <p>Rankability publishes simple pricing and is among the most affordable serious optimisers in the category.</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Plan</th><th>Monthly</th><th>Annual / mo</th><th>Reports/mo</th><th>Seats</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>Starter</strong></td><td>$49</td><td>~$39</td><td>~30</td><td>1</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Pro</strong></td><td>$99</td><td>~$79</td><td>~100</td><td>3</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Agency</strong></td><td>$199</td><td>~$159</td><td>~300</td><td>10 + white-label</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>The annual discount is roughly 20%. The Starter tier is the best entry point in the optimisation-editor category — Surfer Essential is $119/mo and Clearscope starts at $189/mo for comparable scoring depth.</p>

        <h3>The real monthly cost most reviews skip</h3>
        <p>Rankability is cheap. Producing the content it optimises is not.</p>

        <!-- Interactive cost calculator -->
        <div class="cost-calc">
          <div class="cc-head">
            <div>
              <h4>The true monthly cost of SEO content with Rankability</h4>
              <p>Editor + research + writers + publishing. Add it up.</p>
            </div>
            <span class="cc-tag">Per-month math</span>
          </div>
          <div class="cc-rows">
            <div class="cc-row"><span>Rankability Pro</span><strong>$99</strong></div>
            <div class="cc-row"><span>Keyword research (Ahrefs Lite)</span><strong>$129</strong></div>
            <div class="cc-row"><span>Writers — long-form @ $120 each</span><strong>$2,400</strong></div>
            <div class="cc-row"><span>Editor + publishing ops</span><strong>$800</strong></div>
            <div class="cc-row cc-row-total"><span>What you actually spend</span><strong>$3,428 /mo</strong></div>
          </div>
          <div class="cc-vs">
            <span class="cc-vs-label">VS theStacc</span>
            <div class="cc-vs-row">
              <span>theStacc Bundle — all three modules, done for you</span>
              <strong>$167 /mo</strong>
            </div>
            <div class="cc-save">
              <span>You save</span>
              <span><strong>$3,261 /mo</strong> · or <strong>$39,132 / year</strong></span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="cc-foot">
            <p>Want the same output without managing the workflow? Let's see if your site qualifies.</p>
            <a href="/demo/">Get my free audit →</a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="inline-cta dark">
          <div class="cta-copy">
            <h4>Stop scoring articles. Start ranking them.</h4>
            <p>We'll audit your site and show you exactly what would generate the highest ROI for <strong>your</strong> business — DIY tool, agency, or done-for-you platform.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="cta-action">
            <a href="/demo/" class="cta-btn-inline">Book my strategy call <span>→</span></a>
            <span class="cta-meta">30-min · No pitch</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="pros-cons">Pros and cons after 30 days</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>✓ What Rankability gets right</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Starter at $49/mo is the best value in the optimiser category</li>
              <li>NLP scoring methodology is closer to Clearscope than Surfer</li>
              <li>Briefs are tighter and less noisy than Surfer's</li>
              <li>Built by SEO practitioners — opinions baked into the product</li>
              <li>White-label on Agency plan is half the cost of competitors</li>
              <li>AI Draft is grounded in the brief — usable starting point</li>
              <li>Clean, fast editor — no UI bloat</li>
              <li>Real-time scoring as you type</li>
              <li>Strong free trial — you can validate before paying</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>✗ Where Rankability hurts</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>No full keyword research — still need Ahrefs/Semrush</li>
              <li>No site audit, rank tracking, or backlink data</li>
              <li>Smaller user base means fewer tutorials, less community</li>
              <li>AI Draft output needs heavy editing for fact accuracy</li>
              <li>No automated CMS publishing</li>
              <li>SERP insights are thinner than Surfer's full analyser</li>
              <li>Agency white-label is good but not as polished as Clearscope</li>
              <li>Mobile experience is web-only and limited</li>
              <li>Documentation lags feature releases</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="inline-cta">
          <div class="cta-copy">
            <h4>Don't want another optimisation tool to learn?</h4>
            <p>theStacc handles audits, content, publishing, GBP, and rank tracking — without you ever opening a scoring editor. <strong>Try it for $1</strong>, cancel anytime.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="cta-action">
            <a href="/checkout/" class="cta-btn-inline">Start $1 trial <span>→</span></a>
            <span class="cta-meta">No annual contract</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="performance">Performance benchmarks — how Rankability stacks up</h2>
        <p>We optimised the same 10 articles against Rankability, Surfer, and Clearscope. Same writer, same brief inputs, same publishing cadence. Here is what we measured 60 days later.</p>

        <div class="stat-grid">
          <div class="stat-cell">
            <div class="stat-num">$49</div>
            <div class="stat-lbl">/mo Starter price</div>
            <div class="stat-delta">vs Surfer $119</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat-cell">
            <div class="stat-num">~30</div>
            <div class="stat-lbl">Reports / mo Starter</div>
            <div class="stat-delta">~100 on Pro</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat-cell">
            <div class="stat-num">+12</div>
            <div class="stat-lbl">Avg position gain</div>
            <div class="stat-delta">60-day window</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat-cell">
            <div class="stat-num">10</div>
            <div class="stat-lbl">Team seats Agency</div>
            <div class="stat-delta">+ white-label</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3>Rankability vs Surfer vs Clearscope</h3>

        <div class="chart-card">
          <div class="chart-head">
            <div>
              <div class="chart-title">Tool comparison (out of 10)</div>
              <div class="chart-sub">Same 10 articles · scored Apr–May 2026</div>
            </div>
            <div class="chart-legend">
              <span class="lg-1">Rankability</span>
              <span class="lg-2">Competitors</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="bar-rows">
            <div class="bar-row"><span class="bar-label">Scoring accuracy</span><div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill" style="width: 88%"></div></div><span class="bar-value">8.8</span></div>
            <div class="bar-row"><span class="bar-label">Brief quality</span><div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill" style="width: 86%"></div></div><span class="bar-value">8.6</span></div>
            <div class="bar-row"><span class="bar-label">Surfer SEO scoring</span><div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill alt" style="width: 82%"></div></div><span class="bar-value">8.2</span></div>
            <div class="bar-row"><span class="bar-label">Clearscope scoring</span><div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill alt" style="width: 92%"></div></div><span class="bar-value">9.2</span></div>
            <div class="bar-row"><span class="bar-label">Price-to-value</span><div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill" style="width: 94%"></div></div><span class="bar-value">9.4</span></div>
            <div class="bar-row"><span class="bar-label">SEO suite breadth</span><div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill" style="width: 30%"></div></div><span class="bar-value">3.0</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p>Rankability sits between Surfer and Clearscope on scoring quality and beats both on price-to-value. Where it loses is breadth — Surfer bundles audit and SERP analyser; Clearscope brings enterprise editorial workflow. Rankability is intentionally a focused editor.</p>

        <blockquote class="pull">
          "We switched 12 agency clients from Surfer to Rankability. Saved $840/mo, and the briefs are actually less noisy. The catch? We still hire the same writers."
          <cite>— Content lead, B2B SEO agency</cite>
        </blockquote>

        <h2 id="who-its-for">Who Rankability is best for — and who should skip</h2>

        <h3>Strong fit</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>In-house content teams with writers but a tight tools budget</li>
          <li>SEO agencies that want white-label briefs without Clearscope pricing</li>
          <li>Freelance SEOs who have outgrown Surfer Essential pricing</li>
          <li>Marketing teams comfortable assembling Ahrefs + Rankability + a writer</li>
          <li>Anyone who has tried Surfer and wished the scoring was less noisy</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Probably not the right call</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Solo founders without writers (the editor alone produces nothing)</li>
